In "Oliver Twist," mysterious events show what is happening inside Oliver's mind. These moments are like dreams. They show what hurts him and what he knows about the world around him. In chapter 28, Oliver remembers being shot. It feels like a dream. He tries to get help. This shows he had no control over what happened. Oliver's senses are numb, and he does not notice the "unseen hand" that takes him away. The pain is always there, linked with fear. This makes us ask who caused Oliver's problems since it was not him. The shooting shows Oliver has no control. He does not try to change events, even when in danger. This passage hints that Oliver feels defeated, as if Fagin is breaking him. Oliver may be starting to accept despair, which affects how he reacts. If not, Oliver would try to save himself.

"The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as come – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours.

A few years ago, I worked in an after-school program helping young students. I tried my best to help them with any subject they found difficult, but I was best at English and reading. One of the teachers asked me to help a boy named Adrian. I think he was in third or fourth grade. Adrian had a lot of trouble reading. I noticed something strange; he had unusual problems. He could say some letters perfectly, but others not at all. It was very odd. Adrian was Latino, but he spoke perfect English. We worked together until I met his mother. I was watching a few students who did not go on a field trip when Adrian's mother came in. She did not speak English, only Spanish. With my poor Spanish, we could talk a little. Then I realized that Adrian could read fine; he just did not know the English alphabet well. I do not know if this helped Adrian, but I hope he is doing better now.

I share this story to talk about language problems in schools, especially in California. It shows that these problems are not always clear. Even a child who speaks perfect English can have trouble reading it. We know this problem exists, so what can we do? For Adrian, the solution was simple: help with English reading, especially the alphabet and sounds. But for children who barely speak English, it is more complex. There is no one solution. We need to combine different ways: dual language systems, immersion, private tutors, and ESL classes.

First, the dual language system is a good idea. It helps not just children who speak Spanish first, but all children. Children in bilingual programs often do better in school. Some fear it is a waste of resources and helps few children. But that is not true. If we use these programs more, all children will benefit. How do we do this? Do we make all teachers bilingual? No, that is not possible. But we can have special helpers who are bilingual.

From the time we are children, we hear that there is something bigger than us. Some go to Sunday school to learn about it. Others go to Temple or look inside themselves for answers. Many accept the religions from their parents. Some do not. They say there is nothing beyond what they can see. We may follow one belief, then later change to another. Whatever we choose, we try to find a part of ourselves through our view of spirituality. We look for a light to lead us from dark to sun.

"A cardinal," my father said when I asked him his favorite bird. We sat on the porch, listening to rain on the tin roof and smoking. The rain came down, drowning plants by the porch. He looked at the rain, half searching and half remembering. He had grown thinner, and his clothes hung loose. His hair was less than I remembered. He looked at the rain, not at me. I felt alone and afraid. I could not tell my father how much I would miss him because that would make it real. I hugged him, sat again, moved my chair closer, and watched the rain with him in the June twilight.

My father died in December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The treatment did not ease his pain but kept him alive longer than doctors thought. I did not know the value of that extra time. What kind of God would do this, I thought. Alone at night, I said no prayers. If God was there, he did not listen to me.

I did not want to see him go from this life to another. So I did not. I could not watch him leave. I wanted to remember how he lived, not how he died. I knew my father better than others did. I knew he would not want me to watch him die. I stayed in bed for three days and waited.

No one called me.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early supporter of Republicanism. He was mainly a farmer. His work in farming and his time in politics made him known for caring a lot about personal freedom and government. His love for farming shaped almost all his ideas about government. He wanted to keep and grow what he thought was the best job. This influenced his views on who has power, what the Constitution means, and the court system.

John Taylor thought the United States could make a perfect system. He thought this because there was no old way of doing things to stop the makers of the government from creating a system where people rule themselves. He strongly believed in the natural rights of people. He thought these rights depend on each other. If one right is taken away, all rights lose value. These rights should be safe from government control. He said that in a "state of nature," those with strength and bad intentions would benefit. But in a society, this should not happen.

To make this perfect society, Taylor thought a government should be made that considers both the good and bad in people. Taylor had strong views on right and wrong. He said that since humans run the government, all its good and bad traits are human. He said good ideas in government protect private property, help farming, and discourage capitalism. He believed a government with good ideas would work fairly, even if its leaders were greedy. He thought self-interest was what drove people. But it was only bad when it harmed the public good. A good government was needed to control man's bad side, and it needed watching to avoid adding bad ideas.

Taylor, like many Republicans of his time, wanted the Constitution to be followed strictly. He wanted the Federal government to have only the powers clearly given to it in the Constitution. He knew a large Federal government cost a lot and could become unfair. However, he thought a simple reading of the Constitution could be risky. Without thinking about what the writers meant, this way could easily go wrong. He also thought the Declaration of Independence was the true guide for the United States. It showed the country as a group of free states, not just one nation.

I looked down, trying to understand what was in front of me. My mind was calm and quiet. I watched without feeling, studying the view without thinking deeply. Thoughts came and went quickly. It was like I had no real thoughts, just an experience of what I saw.

Once, an artist I knew told me to get a book called The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain. I wanted to learn to draw since I was six. The book teaches many things, from what a pencil is to how the brain sees lines. It says to use a square frame to look at pictures. This makes a detailed picture, like a bowl of fruit on a table in a kitchen, easier to understand by focusing on just the bowl of fruit.

That day, I looked at the bowl in front of me. I could not use the artist’s frame. I was amazed and could only look in wonder. Picasso had a blue period, Monet liked greenery, and Italian masters used many colors. If I wanted to call my view Artistic, this was the start of my story, my Work in Brown.

I touched my chosen tool. My hand moved, and my mind’s idea took shape. Water swirled, clear and clean. Pieces broke away and disappeared. My hand hit the toilet handle again. The brown package did not move, stuck at the bottom.

Holding a mop, feet apart, and a green tie around my neck, I frowned at the mess left in the Rite Aid bathroom. A few more flushes and quiet moments, then I reached for the toilet paper. I wrapped it around my hand like an oven mitt. Standing up, then bending down, my hand slowly went into the bowl, like a mother reaching into an oven for a Thanksgiving turkey.

Teenagers are dying in car accidents. Many reasons come together to make driving dangerous for young American drivers. The National Institutes of Health say one reason is that the teen brain is not ready for driving dangers. Also, teens do not have much driving experience. This lack of experience causes more deadly accidents. It also leads to more rollovers, speeding, and going off the road.  

Teens have more accidents when they drive with friends. Many people know that teens often drive with their friends. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center did a study. It showed a link between the age of passengers and the number of car accidents.  

California and other states try to make teen driving safer. They require temporary licenses. These licenses limit the hours teens can drive. They also do not allow other young passengers.  

But I think these temporary licenses are only a short-term fix. The real problem is that young drivers are not ready for the risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman thinks even 18 years old is too young for a regular license. USA Today says Zuckerman did research that shows young people like to take risks for fun. It makes sense to wait until this risk-taking slows down before allowing teens to drive. If we keep giving licenses to young teens, we will see more deadly accidents. By 2010, many more teens will be old enough to drive.  

Making laws to fix this problem would be simple. Schools could still teach driving classes to help future drivers learn. But no one under 18 should drive a car. A temporary permit could still be given before a full license. Teens should also have to complete a certain number of training hours. This could be based on what most states require now. For example, in California, teens need 6 hours of training with an instructor and 50 hours of practice with an adult.  

The bad statistics for teen drivers come from all states. So, national laws on this issue would protect teens across the country. I think this would be effective. The idea I suggest is not new.

This paper talks about three parts of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, it gives a short definition of the disorder. Next, it explains how to diagnose it, with common signs. Finally, it tells how a teacher can help a student with CAPD in a regular classroom.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also called Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), is about how well the brain uses sound information. It means the brain cannot process sounds correctly. People with CAPD can hear fine, but their brain does not understand sounds well, like separating words from noise.

The first talk about CAPD was in the 1950s. Researchers studied children with communication problems. An Italian team made tests in 1954. In 1961, Kimura made new tests to study how the brain hears sounds. A conference in 1977 helped more research on children with CAPD.

CAPD shows in many ways. A person may not know where a sound comes from. They may have trouble telling sounds apart. They may not notice sound patterns or changes in speech, like sarcasm. One sound may cover another. They may not understand sound clues well or know the order of sounds.

To find out if someone has CAPD, experts watch how they listen and respond to sounds. Audiologists and others use different tests. This may include questions and watching how the person reacts to sounds. There is no single test that works best, and the cause is not known. Tests often have many sounds at once, asking the person to pick out words or numbers. Some tests record ear signals and check responses.

I want to study social work. I hope to work with the Division of Family and Children Services. I want to help children who are abused or neglected. I also want to help families in trouble. I have values that I can bring to social work. These values are service, respect, ethics, and a desire to help others improve their relationships. I also want to improve myself to stay good at my work. These values are important to me, not just to social workers.

I have always wanted to help others, but I was not sure which job to choose. In high school and college, I saw many people run away from their problems. Some used bad ways to cope. Because of this, I decided to study Psychology. I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. After that, I took a break. One day, I visited a friend. She introduced me to a nervous sixteen-year-old boy. He was there to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned he called the police to his parents' home. I went there to see if I could help. I told the police about my concerns. I also said I had a degree in Psychology. The police asked me to talk to the parents since they could not help the boy. The parents seemed nervous. They made excuses for their son’s actions. They called his behavior “manipulative.” This experience made me think about becoming a social worker to help children.

Social justice is also important in social work. We say the individual is important and mourn lost ones. Yet, we often follow old ways instead of being unique. If society mourns lost individuals, why do we try to be like everyone else? I am an individual. I do not want to limit myself to be like others. In high school and college, I fought against social injustice. I colored my hair, wore clothes that showed who I am, and pierced my ears more than usual. I joined GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance). I fought racism and discrimination whenever I saw it. I believe in social justice and will keep fighting against social injustice.

This paper talks about two ways to understand insomnia: the Biological and Sociocultural models. The biological model looks at genes and health. The Sociocultural model looks at how the environment affects race, ethnicity, age, and money. This paper explains research about insomnia and shows how it helps us understand these models. It also talks about what is good and bad about the research.

Sleep problems can be main sleep problems, sleep problems linked to other mental problems, or sleep problems linked to other issues. Main sleep problems are Dyssomnias or Parasomnias. Sleep problems linked to other mental problems are linked to Axis I or Axis II mental issues. Other sleep problems can be due to health issues or drugs. Dyssomnias include: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). Primary Insomnia is trouble sleeping well for at least one month. Primary Hypersomnia is trouble staying awake for the same time. Narcolepsy includes sudden muscle weakness or automatic REM sleep. Dyssomnias are about starting and staying asleep. Parasomnias are about strange behaviors or body functions in sleep. Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. Sleep problems linked to other mental problems involve trouble sleeping because of Axis I (like depression) or Axis II (like personality problems). This paper talks mostly about insomnia and some about main sleep problems with the biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep problems looks at genes, things inherited, and body issues. Neurons in the brain with orexin help control sleep and waking up. A study used mice and found GABAB receptors on orexin neurons that control sleep and wake states. The GABAA receptor helps sleep when it is active. When it is stopped, it can lower anxiety and help sleep. A GABAB agonist (baclofen) made mice sleep more (Matsuki et al., 2009). This means mice studies might help understand humans. There is a genetic and environmental reason for the GABAB receptor in people. A problem with this receptor can make sleep hard without medicine. If genes affect this receptor, it might change sleep naturally. This can hurt life areas like school, work, and tasks that need focus.

I have been a student at University Park for about two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. Getting around campus can be hard for many, including me. In my first year, I lived in East Halls, which is far east on campus. Walking from Stuart Hall to classes in far places like Willard building near the center of campus could take up to 25 minutes, especially in bad weather, which often happens in State College. I talked to a former student who said that East Halls were once separated from the rest of the school by large empty lands. Now, that space has sports fields, big new buildings like the Creamery and health services building, and is surrounded by apartments. As the campus grows, moving around becomes harder. What is the best way to get around? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But just having a bike is not enough. Students need to use them, and the campus needs to be friendly for cyclists.

I talked to a friend who recently started biking again. He said he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride, but it’s the only way to get around.” Bicycling is good for your body and is the fastest way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and some effort can take you 30 miles or more. Like many students, I now live off campus; as far from the center as some dorms. The best choice I made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, which is a 25-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time to 5 minutes if I pedal fast. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the quickest route to Thomas building from my house, and it is not always easy to travel, with or without a bike. Walking has its benefits, but I am too busy to walk. Without my bike, walking would be my only way to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes from my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time spent walking to other classes and appointments. That’s more time than I have.

Aldous Huxley writes about the dangers of technology and capitalism in his book Brave New World. In this story, people care more about the group than the individual. They learn from birth to seek happiness above all. The people are like pieces in a big game, controlled by the World Controller. If you look at the book using Marxist ideas, you see Huxley's worries about these systems. Words from Marxism, such as sameness and making people into things, show that Huxley talks about problems in the economy of his time.

Capitalism is mocked in the book through the idea called false consciousness. This means that people do not see their true place in the economy because they only think about their own gain. This is because they are controlled by ideas like those in Brave New World. The lower classes, like Delta and Gamma, do not have their own will. They are taught to buy, to spend, and to enjoy things above all. The World Controller manages this. The idea of hegemony, where one group controls others, is clear here. The lower classes do not know they are controlled and believe in an idea that keeps capitalism and buying strong. The upper classes know about it but do nothing. Only a few, like Bernard, question their role. The social class interactions show how capitalism oppresses people.

In Brave New World, there are no real relationships between people. Characters are not very deep, even the main ones. Huxley might be saying that technology and capitalism take away free will and expression. Love and strong emotions do not exist. People talk about others in a shallow way, focusing on looks and encounters. Each class is happy with its place, showing the effect of capitalism. Their total obedience to their role in the group shows Marxist ideas. The working class is made to feel superior as long as they keep buying, obeying, and fitting in with others.

Almost four years ago, I took a class on Islam at CBC. One big topic we talked about was if Islam is a hostile religion. I think this question is even more important now. After 9/11, I saw the media change from having a hostile view of Islam and extremists to being very tolerant of Islam in America. I do not think in 2001 we could have had a president with the name Barack Obama, who has a Muslim background in his family.

The story of the Prophet is interesting to me because what I know about Muhammad seems different from his biography. I thought Muhammad forced people to become Muslims. He would take over tribes and make them follow Islam. But in the biography, Muhammad is shown as a kind of martyr, who was misunderstood and humble. People came to him because they believed in his teachings.

There are also some interesting similarities between Jesus and the “miracles” of Muhammad. One is when he made food for forty men from little food. This writing makes me think the writers wanted people to see Muhammad as a humble prophet who did not need to prove anything. This bothers me because it seems to take away from the miracles and life of Jesus Christ. It feels like they are trying to take credit for Jesus's life through Muhammad.

There are also many stories in the biography that try to show proof of people choosing Islam by themselves. But many of these stories are from third-party sources. The author says he heard it from someone who heard it from someone else. I did not like this because it made the stories seem less true and more suspicious.

What bothers me most is that they try to show Muhammad as a godly man who was humble, kind, wise, and gentle. But history shows that Muhammad was not always gentle and humble. I wonder if Muslims today know the true history of Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings and beliefs of Jesus during his life were left behind as Christian thought developed after him. If we look at this history in general, we see Christianity moving away from its start. Today, there is a growing awareness and a new way of thinking. Some people stay with traditional beliefs and do not accept new ideas, but they may not be strong enough to change everything. Among Christians, understanding of history will grow a lot in the future. People will want to know what parts of Christianity came from Jesus and what was added later. It may take a long time, but it will happen: Christianity will return to its original form. A movement will grow that will take away added teachings, one by one, as if time is moving backward, until only what Jesus taught is left. When this change happens in the United States and Europe, many people will start to worship like in the time of Jesus, following only his ideas. The church will still be strong to lead. But because beliefs will go back in time, the many different kinds of Christian beliefs today will become more and more the same. Between regions, between different kinds of churches, we will see more similarities instead of differences. History has many examples of big changes. One example is how Christians were once harmed by the Roman Empire, but later Rome became Christian. Our country changed from having African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The big change in the future will happen in the Christian religion, going back to the start and making beliefs more the same. This process will happen by reading Jesus' words as symbols, not just as they are. What happened after Jesus' time? If we look back in history, we find Judaism, the start of the Christian religion. Belief in one God, the idea of a revealed religion, and the authority of Hebrew writings were important by the time Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. Jewish people were not all the same. They were divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and many common people.

I think The Jungle shows that people are naturally greedy and selfish. They care only about themselves and want to make their lives better. They do not care for others who are less fortunate. The Jungle shows this in many ways. The most obvious example is the owners and managers of the big factories. They want to make their companies and factories as big and successful as possible. They do not care about anyone who gets hurt in the process. Upton Sinclair writes about this: "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." Sinclair is trying to show the damage caused by pollution. The owners do not care about people or animals hurt by the smoke or waste from the factories. 

The owners and managers also do not care about their workers who make them rich. They will do anything to make more money. Sinclair writes, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." They force workers to work long hours and then fire them without notice or help. During the time The Jungle is set in, there were few, if any, laws to protect workers. This let managers and owners push workers hard and make them work in bad conditions. The book does not say it directly, but workers in Packingtown were expected to endure these terrible conditions both at work and at home. There were no groups to help or inform the workers. Some unions were formed, but they often took money from the poor workers. The workers were so badly treated and trapped in the system that they were like slaves. Sinclair writes, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

"Dream-Land" is a poem by Edgar Allan Poe. Poe liked this poem a lot. In "Dream-Land," Poe uses the word "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56. Mabbott says this word comes from Virgil. Virgil used "Thulé" to talk about an island north of Britain. The Greeks thought this island was the edge of the known world. Virgil did use this term. But there is another source that is important too. Poe liked German writers. 

This is important because it shows Poe knew Goethe's writing. Karl J. Arndt wrote a book called Poe’s Politian and Goethe’s Mignon. Arndt says Poe's poem is like Goethe's poem. He thinks Poe was copying Goethe. The Oxford Companion to English Literature says Goethe was a famous writer. He wrote the poetic drama "Faust." "Faust" was in two parts. The first was published in 1808. The second was published in 1832, the year Goethe died. 

In the second part of "Faust," there is a short poem called "The King of Thulé." This poem is about a king. His wife dies after giving him a goblet. After she dies, he drinks a lot and cries for her. He decides to die and gives his things to his children. He keeps the goblet. He walks to a cliff, throws the goblet into the sea, closes his eyes, and dies. The king in "The King of Thulé" and the king in "Dream-Land" are similar. They both show loss and sadness. "Faust" was made into a play by H. P. Grattan in 1842. This was before Poe used "Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum."

Poe uses "Thule" twice in his writings. He says "ultima Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum." He also uses it in "Dream-Land" twice, at the start and end of the poem. "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" can be read together. In "Dream-Land," the speaker talks about Thule. It is dark and lonely. He sees dead friends and a world without color. These scenes are like "The King of Thulé" by Goethe. The king there loses his wife and feels lonely. He loses his will to rule or live. The poem sounds like the speaker is inside Goethe's poem.

Goethe was an important writer. Poe knew about him, maybe because he respected Tennyson. Poe once said he admired Tennyson. Aside from Tennyson, Poe would have seen Goethe's work in many copies made after it was first published.

In California, can a customer who got hurt after slipping on an applesauce spill in a grocery store get extra damages if the store manager acted with bad intent? The manager was told twice about the spill but did not clean it up for thirty minutes because he was eating dinner.

A judge might not immediately dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for extra damages. To ask for extra damages, a person must show that the other person acted with a willful disregard for likely harm, and that the behavior was very bad. Palmer can say Martin should have known the danger of not cleaning a spill because other customers had slipped in the past. Even with this knowledge, he did not clean the spill. Palmer's argument that Martin's actions were very bad is less strong but still reasonable since there were six slip-and-fall incidents in 2009, and Martin still did not keep his store safe.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, Rich Wayne, a worker at D&D Markets, told his manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin said he was on a dinner break and "didn't have time to deal with customer complaints." At 5:15 pm, another worker, Mary J. Haddigan, also told Mr. Martin about the spill, and Martin responded the same way. At 5:30 pm, the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer, slipped on the spill and hurt her back badly. Before Palmer's accident, five other slip-and-fall incidents happened at D&D's in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for damages related to her injury, and we are looking at whether to ask the judge to dismiss the claim for extra damages.

In California, a person can get extra damages for breaking an obligation if the other person acted with "oppression, fraud or malice." The law says malice is when someone meant to cause harm, or if not, the action must be "very bad" and done with a "willful disregard for the rights or safety of others." Courts say actions are malicious when done with disregard for the person's rights, when the other person "was aware of the likely dangerous results of his actions, and still did not try to avoid them."

She always felt like she needed something. It was a desire that never went away. It started when she was 14, just entering her teenage years. At 17, she still felt it. She knew she wanted someone, not something. But she had no interest in boys. Some boys liked her and tried to win her over, but she did not like them back. She often asked herself why she felt this way. She thought about it for years but found no good answer. So she lived her life, always wondering about her wants.

Her days at home were usually calm. Her parents were good, quiet people. They did not argue with each other. They rarely argued with her. The only thing they argued about was her need for independence and freedom. She was the daughter of a calm couple, but she was lively and fun. People liked her because she was nice.

But today was not calm. As she moved from room to room, looking for new ideas, she heard a scream from the kitchen. It was her mother's voice. She ran into the room, feeling scared. "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" she asked. She saw her mother on the floor, in pain, saying "Ow" over and over. The daughter ran to her mother and tried to help. "Ouch ... sweetie, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital." Her mother spoke with difficulty, and the daughter knew she was in great pain. "Okay Mom, just tell me how I can help." Her mother pointed, and the daughter was glad she was strong. She carried her mother to the car, laid her in the back, and drove.

The hospital smelled of disinfectant and sickness, mixed with fear. But she did not notice it. Her mind was focused on helping her mother. She carried her mother quickly and called for doctors. Some worried faces came over, and someone brought a rolling bed. They laid her mother on it and took her away to be checked. The daughter sat and waited, worried.

Her mother had fallen off a stool while trying to reach a vase from the top cabinet.

This study aimed to show that following a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), with a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," is linked to a lower risk of long-term heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as death from stroke. The aMed diet is a changed version of the Med diet. It includes more plant foods, such as plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fat (instead of saturated fat), and fish. It includes fewer animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol intake is allowed.

Earlier studies showed that following a Med diet was linked to a lower risk of death from all causes and heart-related causes. An intervention trial showed that the Med diet worked better than a low-fat diet for weight loss and reducing the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese people. Earlier studies did not focus on stroke or death from stroke.

This study followed 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, without a history of heart disease or diabetes. They are part of the Nurses' Health Study, a group study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states. From 1984 to 2004, the authors calculated an aMed diet score six times using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) to check nutrient intake during the previous year. Over 95% of nurses stayed in the study for 20 years. FFQs were checked for accuracy. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed by looking at medical or hospital records, autopsy, or death certificates. If records were not available, cases were called "probable" and included. About 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal heart attacks were classified as probable. For each FFQ, body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin use, menopausal status, and postmenopausal hormone use were calculated. From 1986, leisure-time physical activity was also checked.

To reduce random changes for a person and better show long-term diet intake, average aMed scores from several FFQs were calculated. This included scores from two years before. Changes were made for "confounders" (factors that could affect results) by adjusting for age, smoking, body mass index, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin use, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to check the link between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Higher adherence to the Mediterranean diet, shown by a higher aMed diet score, was linked to a lower risk of new CHD and stroke in women. During 20 years of follow-up, there were 2391 new cases of CHD, 1763 new cases of stroke, and 1077 deaths from cardiovascular disease (fatal CHD and strokes combined). Women in the top aMed group were at lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom group (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

The sign says that Hitler is alive in Burma.

Ellen Page, star of the movie Juno, stands alone at a street corner. She holds a piece of cardboard over her head. The unsettling message is written with a Sharpie on her sign. Burma, also called Myanmar, is a country in Southeast Asia. A military junta rules it. They took power in 1962 through a coup. In 2007, there were street protests. These were the first public protests in ten years. A large number of Burmese monks led these protests. They were called "The Saffron Revolution" because of the color of the monks' robes. After the first few protests, more people in Burma became interested. At first, the government let the monks gather peacefully. But soon, violence grew. The military and monks clashed. The army even invaded monasteries. Foreign journalists were arrested. A Japanese photojournalist, Kenji Nagai, was killed on September 27, 2007, at a protest. The official death toll says 13 people died. But Colonel Hla Win, who left the army before the report, said many more people died. He said the number of dead could be several thousand.

This is not new. Governments have tried to stop dissent and keep control of people for a long time. Roman emperors said gods chose them to rule. Japanese emperors were thought to be gods. They were said to lead people to prosperity. And the president, George W. Bush, talks weekly with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, which is part of the Republic Party.

Some well-known examples of these actions include the 1989 protest at Tiananmen Square. Intellectuals, labor activists, and students protested the government's rule. The death toll varies. Chinese government reports say 200-300 died. The Chinese Red Cross says 2,000-3,000 died. Another example is the Rwandan genocide in the 1990s. Hutu militia, helped by the government, started killing Tutsis and political moderates. Hitler's 'Third Reich' is another extreme example. It was a time when people of Jewish background were killed. This happened over several years and in many countries.

Duke Ellington was important in jazz for many years. He was good at leading his band. Ellington played the piano in a quiet way in many songs. But he was great at writing music that showed the talents of his band members. He made songs where solo players could improvise. He also wrote music that fit the style of his band. This helped create a clear and new sound for each piece. Ellington knew how each player sounded and how they worked together. This helped him write some of the best jazz music.

The Grove Music dictionary talks about Ellington's sound and new ideas. It mentions "Creole Love Call." In this song, Ellington used voice as a jazz instrument. This was one of the first times he used voice to add feeling and color without words. "Creole Love Call" also shows how Ellington worked well with his soloists. This song is a slow twelve-bar blues with six parts:

Part 1: The voice and reeds talk to each other. The voice starts smooth and then gets rough.
Part 2: A trumpet plays a solo with a soft sound, adding blue notes.
Part 3: A clarinet plays high notes with soft piano in the background.
Part 4: The full band repeats the first part with brass and reeds talking to each other.
Part 5: The reeds start high notes, with brass and rhythm sections playing in syncopated stop time.
Part 6: Like the first part, with voice and reeds talking to each other. The voice uses a "growl" sound like an instrument.
End: A short vocal run and a unique trombone ending.

Ellington used voice to add color to his music often. In "Hot and Bothered," recorded a year later, Ellington used tight band play and a good ear for tone color. A trumpet and singing part talk to each other, using the voice of the trumpet and the trumpet sound of the voice. This made a rich and fitting sound. "It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing)" used these ideas too. Ellington used Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton to start the melody on muted trombone.

Why do living things change over time in the way they do? Are there limits that affect how they change? In 1917, D'Arcy Thompson said, "Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms." This is still true today. Recently, math models have been used to study how mollusks form their shells over time. Our study looks at how using math models with study experiments can show how changes happen in Prunum. We used X-ray pictures of Prunum to find numbers that help us make models of shell shapes. These numbers were put into a computer program called CerioShell. We made models of shell shapes to understand how Prunum can change. We combine these results with other studies to better know big changes in this group.

A shell is like a tube that turns around over time. These turns are called whorls, and they go around an imaginary line called the columella. Whorls can grow at different speeds, and a line called a suture separates each whorl. The biggest whorl is usually the last one, or the body whorl. The spire is all the whorls except the last one. The tip of the spire is the apex, and the end is the base. The animal comes out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be seen from different views: apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural. The usual way to look at a shell is in the apertural view, with the opening facing you and the apex pointing up.

To count whorls, first look at the shell from the top and find where the first suture starts. Draw a line to divide the shell in two. Count the whorls from this line, estimating to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of openings that move through time and space as the animal builds its shell. You can trace the path of the opening by looking at the center of each whorl's opening and its size.

This path can be shown with pictures and math. Once there is a math model, you can change numbers to see how the mollusk makes its shell.

The number of babies and young children who die in Indonesia has not changed much in the last ten years. The country is doing well in some goals, like water and sanitation. But it is not doing well in child and mother health. It needs to do better to meet the goals by 2015. Many reasons explain why this is so. They show that Indonesia should make the health system stronger instead of just focusing on specific programs.

Indonesia has made progress in having skilled health workers at births. Now, 72% of births have skilled workers. But this number includes traditional workers, like midwives, who cannot help if there are problems in pregnancy. This is why many mothers die from bleeding. So, the numbers look better than they are. There is still much work to do. Also, fewer children under five with diarrhea are treated by health workers. Information on care after birth is not complete. But it shows that this area also needs attention, with low numbers across the country.

Rates of c-section births are still lower than expected, about 4%. In cities, it is 7%, but in rural areas, it is only 2%. This shows that healthcare access is better in cities than in rural areas. Another issue is that poor people find it harder to get healthcare. There is a 27% difference in service use between the poorest and richest people. This is likely because of costs.

To improve care for babies and mothers, we need to ask how to best deal with the lack of service. Should Indonesia make specific programs, or should it make the whole health system stronger? Programs that focus on one area are appealing. They have clear goals and often show quick results. But there are problems. If we spend too much on one program, other areas may get less money. Workers may move to the area with more resources. Running many programs for the same area can lead to repeated and uncoordinated services. This means more forms and paperwork for supplies and funding.

Over the past 100 years, Popular Music has grown to include many types. It is hard to list them all. Each type, like rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, has many smaller groups. One small group, Heavy Metal rock, has become very different and full of expression in the last 40 years. It shows many feelings, often dark ones. Heavy Metal is different because it can change. Soon after it started, people saw it could be flexible. They used it to make their own new kinds of Heavy Metal. This led to even more new kinds, and this continues today.

Today, Heavy Metal has so many small groups that it is hard to say what Heavy Metal is. It has taken ideas from many other types of music. But, it started somewhere. To understand metal music today, one must know what the metal movement is and why it is a movement, not just a type of music.

Metal is a movement that shows darkness. It is music with more bass, more sound, more force, and more show. Metal musicians know how to play well, and you can hear it. Metal is also linked with drugs. In the mid-70s, many people used drugs, which led to wild, strange records. These records had qualities that were new to music because most popular music did not have dark emotions. Later metal got some ideas from the dark qualities of the Romantic Era. Lyrics in songs like Helter Skelter show this darkness.

The song Helter Skelter by the Beatles shows their darker side. It talks about ups and downs, like the effects of drugs. Some say it is one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was made in response to a Rolling Stones song that was also dark and heavy. The Beatles wanted to show they could be heavy too, so they put this song on The White Album.

A few decades before Surrealist artists began painting dreamlike pictures, the artist Henri Rousseau was making his own dreams. The Dream is a painting from 1910 by the famous Post-Impressionist artist. It shows a woman amazed by the wonders in a dream world. It also shows Rousseau's own dreams and goals as a painter. He wanted other artists and art lovers to recognize and praise his work. He had a hard time because he wanted to be accepted. The Dream shows Rousseau's struggle: to follow popular painting styles or to be different and unique.

To understand The Dream, one needs to know Rousseau's life story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer. Rousseau did not get formal art training. He worked for France as a municipal toll employee until he was forty. People mistakenly called him a customs inspector. After his first wife, Clémence, died, along with eight infant children, Rousseau was left with one daughter, Julia, and much sadness. He then turned to painting for comfort and a new start. Unlike other artists who romanticized the peasant life, Rousseau was a folk painter with the dreams of an average person in his class.

Rousseau wanted to be accepted by the art world. This is understandable because he had no formal art education and started painting later in life. He worked at the same time as many talented artists. Rousseau did not get much recognition until Matisse became known. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon says Matisse and Rousseau were different. Matisse feared painting in a common way, while Rousseau wanted to paint in a style that would let him join the Artiste Français.

Many great thinkers say there is a close link between ethics and beauty, between truth and beauty. I think there is a reason for this. John Keats says in "Ode on a Grecian Urn," "Beauty is truth, truth beauty." We learn much in life from school or our experiences. Yet, we seem to understand ethics and beauty, as Keats says, without being taught in the usual ways. Ethics and beauty try to describe, not tell us what to do. Our studies of right and wrong and beauty mostly try to explain why art or writing is beautiful or why an action is right. They are not rules for making good art or acting well.

Criticism of art or morals never fully explains what is good or beautiful. Talking about da Vinci's "Mona Lisa" might include ideas like foreground, background, or contrast, but these do not fully explain why it is good art. When asked about a favorite piece of art or writing, people often say, "There's just something about it" before giving a deeper explanation. I think art and morals cannot be fully described by their features. Flannery O'Connor says, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." Even if we describe a piece of writing fully, there is always something beyond that. I think ethics has this same quality. Wittgenstein says, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental." I suggest that this "something," this special quality, is the strongest part of art and morality, and that this special nature of both connects them.

I believe that morality and art are so close because we feel both deeply at a level we cannot fully explain. This link is stronger in the art of writing. McKean says, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Today, Germany is a strong and united country. It has a special culture. This culture is found from the Alps in München to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel. It is also in Köln near the Rhine, through the center of Germany, to Dresden on the Elbe. Germany’s culture comes from many different tribes and groups.

Germania is the old land of the Germans. The name's origin is debated by scholars. Tacitus said it came from a tribe called Tungrians. They were known as Germans before crossing the Rhine to fight the Gauls. Julius Caesar used the word "Germanus" in his writings about the Gallic Wars. He used it to tell apart the Gauls and the Germanic tribes. Some say the name comes from a Gaulish word for neighbor. Caesar wrote about the Germans and the Gauls fighting often. Others think the name comes from the spear called a "ger" or the Old Irish word "garim" meaning "to shout."

Tacitus, a Roman historian, wrote about the origins of Germans in AD 98. He said Germans were native to their land and not mixed with other races. He noted that people would not leave places like Asia or Africa for Germany unless it was their home.

The Romans did not move to Germania. They sent conquests for goods and sometimes led land campaigns. But they mostly returned to their empire. In the first century, Germanic tribes lived near the Roman Empire. They traded goods and served in the Roman army.

The play "Twelfth Night" shows that while disguise is useful for deception, in the end, a person must stop pretending. If not, they might lose themselves. Ending a deception can make someone feel alone. So, a person must choose between keeping their true self or keeping relationships. Some people will not mind being tricked, but others will be upset.

The topic of deception in changing gender roles is difficult. It raises questions, like why a person feels they need to pretend to be another gender. In Viola's case, it is to protect herself: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249).

In a new place, Viola pretends to be a man to stay safe. Her plan works, but it separates her from other women, cutting her off from support. It gets worse when Olivia mistakes her for Sebastian and falls in love with her: “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138). Viola also struggles with her feelings for Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261).

To some readers today, "Twelfth Night" shows how deception can reveal hidden emotions, especially for Olivia and Orsino. Some parts suggest these characters have unspoken desires that Viola/Cesario helps them face. Is Olivia drawn to Cesario because Cesario seems to be a man, or does Olivia have feelings for women? It is likely not the case. Shakespeare’s Olivia might be mocking those who judge by looks.

This is clear when Olivia quickly shifts her love from Cesario to Sebastian, and sees Cesario/Viola as family, not a lover: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315).

German rule in Africa was often very harsh. In German South West Africa, there was a genocide against the Ovaherero and Nama people. However, not all German colonies were the same. Each had different rules and ways of governing. Education in the colonies was also different. When the British took over German East Africa in 1919, they found many educated Africans. German education efforts in Kamerun were praised by writers at the time.

South West Africa was different. In East Africa, the government made schools for native people. But in South West Africa, missionaries ran schools for natives with little help from the government. The government spent a lot on schools for Europeans in the colony. They set up state schools and supported missionary schools for Europeans.

These education policies had long-term effects. In South West Africa, most people stayed uneducated. Other colonies had more literate Africans. Various reasons caused this difference in South West Africa. This paper looks at these reasons and new research on how settlers and officials saw native Africans.

There is much writing about education in German colonies. Most of it is in German from the early 1900s. These works described the education systems. Later English works compared education in different colonies and looked at specific details. They showed big differences in education systems. Cohen’s study is a key work. It looks at education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen says the large settler population in South West Africa explains many of its education system features.

South West Africa had a somewhat mild climate, though much of it is desert. By 1913, nearly 15,000 Europeans lived there. In East Africa, the next largest settler colony, only 5,336 Europeans lived.

The United States and Mexico were once two nations with a long rivalry. This rivalry lasted 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. The biggest event in this rivalry was the Mexican-American War from 1846 to 1848. During this war, the United States attacked and won against Mexico. The U.S. gained Texas and the American Southwest. There were other fights between the two nations, but they stopped just before World War I. The rivalry started because Americans and Mexicans had different views on religion, culture, and other important issues.

This situation is similar to other countries that have long rivalries with neighbors. Countries that share borders often have conflicts of interest. These conflicts can lead to rivalries. The United States and Mexico are like many other countries with border rivalries. David M. Pletcher says that only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting American diplomatic problems. Both countries are close to the U.S. and have been rivals, while other Latin American countries have had good relations with the U.S.

Religious issues created problems between the U.S. and Mexico. This is a common problem throughout history. Sally Frahm says that in the 20th century, Americans opposed fascism and communism. In the 18th and 19th centuries, they opposed Catholicism and monarchy. Like the Cold War with the Soviet Union, the U.S. and Mexico had both ideological and interest-based struggles. But, their struggles were more about religion than political structures. The distrust between English and Spanish people carried over to the U.S. and Mexico. This made it hard for the two countries to have good relations.

Diehl and Goerts list 17 disputes between the U.S. and Mexico during their rivalry. Most of these were about border issues, like raids from Mexico into the U.S. Border raids by bandits were a big problem. These raids continued until both countries used military force to control their borders. Schmitt says that the rivalry started to end when Mexico became dependent on the U.S. This happened because American goals changed from territorial expansion to economic activity in Mexico in the late 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I became disabled by an illness I did not know about. 

I was a nurse then. I chose this job because I wanted safety and security I did not have when I was a child. People told me, "You will always find work because people will always get sick." I heard this many times as I grew up. So, even though I wanted to be a scientist or a journalist, I chose nursing. 

But then, I was 46 years old and single, with no money saved, and I could not work. I am still disabled and have lived on Social Security Disability for 15 years. I have nothing left that I can call "mine." I get by, but every day is hard. Nothing in my life is sure now, but I know one thing is true. I could not have managed all these years without help from my family and a few good friends, even if I was strong. When real trouble comes, you do not feel strong. 

My point is that life will always have emergencies, big and small. There are no guarantees. No matter how well one prepares, some things are too big to handle alone. 

I agree that in the U.S., we should not rely only on big government. It is not working well. But I would rather see Americans learn to trust each other again. We should help each other and ask for help, instead of each person building a fallout shelter alone. 

In the U.S., some people talk about "rugged individualism." But really, what kept people going in hard times was compassion, respect, and sharing. Pioneers who crossed the Rockies did not make it to the coast alone. 

So, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit, first aid supplies, water purifying tablets, plastic sheeting, and tape for the windows in case of a biological attack. I have flashlights, batteries, candles, waterproof matches, and canned goods. If you have land and resources for a small farm, and can preserve your own food, do it. It is a good idea, as is a wood stove, if you do not live in an apartment. 

But also, get to know your neighbors.

A long time ago, in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born. This prince would later be called Buddha. During his life, he left the world he knew and found wisdom. His ideas led to Buddhism. The oldest form of Buddhism is called Theravada Buddhism. This religion is about two thousand five hundred years old. It has changed since Buddha lived. We can see this change in places like Sri Lanka. There, people take part in a special water-cutting ceremony each year. Both monks and regular people join in. This ceremony is important to them, even though Buddha did not teach about such events. These changes are in both the traditions people follow and the basic beliefs of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist group, including both monks and non-monks, has had to change its beliefs over time. This is because of many different reasons, both from within and from outside, and both friendly and unfriendly.

We will use some terms often in this discussion. Internal means something that comes from inside the Buddhist group. External means something that comes from outside the Buddhist group. A hostile force is something that harms or wants to harm Buddhism. A benign force does not want to harm or help Buddhism, but it might do so by accident. We will use these words a lot as we talk.

First, we need to look at the basic ideas of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists believe in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma includes the Tripitaka, which is three parts of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka has all the teachings, the Vinaya Pitaka has the rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka has the deeper ideas of Buddhism. These deeper ideas include things like Anatta, which means no soul, Dukkha, which means life has suffering, and Anicca, which means everything changes. By understanding these ideas, one can stop the cycle of death and rebirth, called Sansara. When this cycle stops, so does desire, hatred, and delusion, and one becomes wise. The Vinaya Pitaka gives rules for how to live. Regular people follow five rules: do not kill, do not lie, do not steal, do not behave badly in relationships, and do not use drugs. Monks have many more rules. The most important idea in Buddhism is the four noble truths. First, Dukkha, the truth that life has suffering. Second, that wanting things causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be ended.
